Removal

Removing NAs from the spotify data set:

# selecting the variables we need: 
spotsub = 
  select(spotdata, liveness, energy, mode, danceability, valence, key, genre, duration_ms, tempo);
# only 4 rows are missing
sum( !complete.cases(spotsub))
## [1] 4
# throwing out the rows
spotsub = spotsub[ complete.cases(spotsub), ]
# confirming there are no missing values
colSums(  is.na(spotsub))

All the NAs have not been removed and a new data frame named spotsub is now free to use without any NA values.

Dataset Description

The source of this data set was pulled from Spotifys API and manipulated into a csv file by Lily Carew approximately one year ago to todays date: March 20, 2023. The data set includes a representation of a songs characteristics and each row is represented by a song. Upon NA value removal there were 10130 songs and after NA value removal there are 10127 songs left in the data set. There are in total 17 columns plus 5 columns I decided to remove. The 5 columns were unnecessary considering they are included information about the api retrieval. There are only 7 areas I am currently interested in which are: liveness, energy, mode, danceability, valence, key, genre. These columns will be used more often then others. Thenumerical columns include: liveness, energy, mode, danceability, valence. Then there is the categorical columns which include : key, genre. The spotify data set provided was derived from a variety of songs that were release one year ago so considering this data was collected, it can be characterized as ramdonized expiremental data.

Distribution of energy for each genre

If we observe the distribution of each graph visually we can see that the genres that lacks the most energy is classical and jazz which is reasonable considering the settings in which the genre is most suitable at. Jazz is more surprising considering there are jazz pieces with high energy. We can also see that rock and popular are more right heavy meaning they are more energetic genres.

##Confidence Intervals Shown below are the 95 percent confidence intervals for the variable valence. Using the function created below we are able to calculate the left tail and right tail of the data.

spotsub %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=valence, color = genre)) + 
              geom_density(show.legend = FALSE) +
              xlim(c(0), 1) + 
  facet_wrap(~genre) + labs(title = "Distribution of Valence for each genre");

sigma = 1.1;
ex = spotsub %>%
  group_by(genre)%>%
    summarise(meanvalence = mean(valence), num = n());

ex = mutate(ex, Leftend = meanvalence - 1.96*sigma/sqrt(num))
ex = mutate(ex, Rightend = meanvalence + 1.96*sigma/sqrt(num))

ex %>%
  kbl() %>%

Hypothesis testing

\(H_0:\) \(\mu\) = 0.438

\(H_A:\) \(\mu\) < 0.438

\(H_0:\) the population average of valence. \(H_A:\) using the sample average, the valence population average should be less than 0.438. Taking the sample average of valence of classical music, the population mean should be less than 0.438

#population mean
uValence = 0.438;
#sample mean
xValence = 0.221;

sdValence = 0.208;
n = 740;

z = function(x, u, sd, n){
  return (x-u)/(sd/sqrt(n));
}

sr = spotsub%>%
  group_by(genre)%>%
    summarise(meanVal = mean(valence), sdVal = mean(valence)) 

length(sr)
## [1] 3
for(i in length(sr))
  
z(xValence, uValence, sdValence, n);

the Z value given is -0.217 > -1.64 which means that it fails to reject the null hypothesis. Given this conclusion of the hypothesis, this mean that classical music is not inherently sadder than all musical genres combined.

Line of best fit for the Relationship between valence and energy

Shown below is the scatter plot of the relationship between valence and energy. Theoretically these two variables should share a vary vivid relationship. Show below is a scatter plot of Valence versus Energy and the regression line that shows best fit. Furthermore the graph is broken down into independant facets that share similar regression lines but vary in its coefficients. The total regression line for the graph Valence versus Energy show a positive relationship meaning as energy increases the mood of the song approaches positiveness. The relationship between each subset of genres also point to this conclusion as each regression line follow a similarity between the relationship of each point. What one can observe is the relationship of each genres slope. What does electronic genre with a derivative of 0.22 versus pop with a derivative of 0.08 tell us about the relationship of valence and energy for each genre? Considering that pops regression line grows faster than electronic, one can say that there is more variety but less complexity between the feeling of the music, meaning that there are tracks either with very energetic with a positive atmosphere and very slow with a mellow atmosphere. Electronic can be more contemporary meaning there is no clear line whether it has a positive atmosphere or negative atmosphere.

Total Regression Valence vs Energy

n = spotsub%>%
      group_by(genre) %>%
         do(fittedmodel = lm(valence ~ energy, data = .))

wholemodel = lm(valence ~ energy, data = spotdata)

plot8 = 
  ggplot(spotsub , aes(x= energy, y = valence)) + 
  geom_point() +
  geom_abline(intercept = wholemodel$coefficients[1],
              slope = wholemodel$coefficients[2], color="red") + 
  labs(title = "Valence vs. Energy")
